n name from legacyuo.com to firasimus.com. I was preemptive and began changing the conf files located in Nginx to prepare for the move. All I had to do was make :</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Server {</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Listen 80;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">server_name www.legacyuo.com legacyuo.com;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Into:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Server {</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Listen 80;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">server_name firasimus.com www.firasimus.com;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Easy enough.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Everything seemed to have been working except for the fact that my Wordpress /wp-admin was pointing to my old domain name. It was an easy fix. Log into Admin,  Go to Settings and change the of Wordpress Address(URL) and Site Address (URL) to the corresponding domain name.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I\'ll be working on allowing Nginx ( which is a web server, the very program that\'s \"running\" this website right now) to use .htaccess for extra security on my \"wp-admin\" page. I believe Nginx by default does not use .htaccess. The original purpose of .htaccess—reflected in its name—was to allow per-directory access control, by for example requiring a password to access the content.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Battle 1:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Firasimus vs .htaccess&amp;Nginx</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr valign=\"top\">\r\n<th scope=\"row\"></th>\r\n<td></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr valign=\"top\">\r\n<th scope=\"row\"></th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','And so it begins','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-v1','','','2013-11-28 16:13:19','2013-11-28 16:13:19','',1,'http://firasimus.com/?p=10',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2013-12-16 21:40:07','2013-12-16 21:40:07','There\'s been a lot that I have been figuring out that I probably should have took the time to document while doing it. First off, I learned how to mount files via an NFS ( Network File Share System). I\'m going to re-trace my steps and re-do everything just for the sake of learning and documenting it. This of course, required my to purchase my second VPS.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI\'ll work backwards here. To unmount the NFS - you essentially have to stop ALL services using it. I began with:\r\n\r\nservice nginx stop\r\n\r\nservice php-fpm stop\r\n\r\numount /mount/nfs ( unmounting the current mount)\r\n\r\nBefore I was able to do any of this I had to setup NFS on the hosting/master server. I began with:\r\n\r\nyum install nfs-utils nfs-utils-lib\r\n\r\nchkconfig nfs on ( to make sure service starts if theres a restart)\r\n\r\nservice rpcbind start\r\n\r\nservice nfs start (Starts the required service, which is obviously NFS)\r\n\r\nTo share a directory we would open /etc/exports and add the following line to the file:\r\n\r\n/mount/nfs IP.ADDRESS.OF.CLIENT(rw, sync, no_root_squash,no_subtree_check)\r\n\r\nRemember, PAY ATTENTION THAT IT IS THE IP OF THE CLIENT, NOT THE MASTER. It\'s basically allowing the IP to remotely connect.\r\n\r\nThese settings accomplish several tasks:\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>rw:</b> This option allows the client server to both read and write within the shared directory</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>sync:</b> Sync confirms requests to the shared directory only once the changes have been committed.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b> no_subtree_check:</b> This option prevents the subtree checking. When a shared directory is the subdirectory of a larger filesystem, nfs performs scans of every directory above it, in order to verify its permissions and details. Disabling the subtree check may increase the reliability of NFS, but reduce security.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><b>no_root_squash:</b> This phrase allows root to connect to the designated directory</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nI then save the file, and exit.\r\n\r\nFollowed up with:\r\n\r\nexportfs -a (exports/shares \"all/-a\" files/directories in the /exports file, which is /mount/nfs)\r\n\r\nWe are now done with the \"Master Client\" and the files should be shared over a network.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMoving on to the client(which is what I unmounted or \"umount /mount/nfs\" earlier.\r\n\r\nNaturally, you will want to install the service.\r\n\r\nyum install nfs-utils nfs-utils-lib\r\n\r\nYou then create the folder where you want the mounted files to be placed. For me, it was /mount/nfs/.(Yes, it\'s the same folder as the master so that it\'s easy for me.)\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can mount it via IP.ADDRESS.HERE:/mount/nfs and it will be mounted. HOWEVER, you want to go into /etc/fstab and place the configuration in there. The reason for this is should the service/server restart it will automatically mount the hosted NFS files.\r\n\r\nSo,\r\n\r\nnano /etc/fstab\r\n\r\nadd in 162.243.67.60:/mount/nfs /mount/nfs     nfs     defaults        0 0\r\n\r\nSave the file, and exit.\r\n\r\nAgain, you can use mount /mount/nfs. Another way is mount -a which is \"mount all files in the configuration(Fstab)\" which should be only the one we currently added.\r\n\r\nYou can then use df -h to check the files have been added properly. Additionally, you can use mount to see the lists of all the mounted files.\r\n\r\nTo test if it\'s working from the CLIENT run this:\r\n\r\ntouch /mount/nfs/example\r\n\r\nThen go to the Master server and:\r\n\r\nls /mount/nfs\r\n\r\nthe file \"example\" should show up. Of course, just replace all this with your own files/directories, it should be pretty simple.\r\n\r\nThis allowed me to copy my web server files. I copied them into /mount/nfs/firasmus/html.\r\n\r\nFrom there, I began to work on the remote hosting of MySQL so that the second VPS can access it(or any amount of VPS\'s should I add more). For the sake of organization, I\'ll do that in another post.','Been busy','','publish','open','open','','been-busy','','','2013-12-16 21:40:07','2013-12-16 21:40:07','',0,'http://firasimus.com/?p=24',0,'post','',0),(23,1,'2013-12-16 21:01:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2013-12-16 21:01:27','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://firasimus.com/?p=23',0,'post','',0),(16,1,'2013-12-01 18:52:19','2013-12-01 18:52:19','<blockquote>Use the find command with the -perm option to locate five setuid files on your system. For each file, explain why the setuid mechanism is necessary for the command to function properly.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt took me a bit to figure out the proper command to run because I didn\'t know what variable to place in the find command. After a bit of research, I still had some trouble but I\'ll try to explain it as best as possible.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI ran \"find / -perm +4000\" because that\'s what most results told me to do, I didn\'t understand it until I looked a little further. 4000 represents setuid and 2000 represents setgid. (Often times, we\'ll see commands combine both to 6000(4000+2000=6000)). The output confused me a bit because I was seeing a lot of \"Permission Denied\".\r\n\r\nI then ran this command : find / -perm -4000 -exec ls -ldv {} \\; &gt; /tmp/setuidsearch\r\n\r\nI later found that I enjoyed the more immediate display via : find / -perm -4000 -type f -print0 | xargs -0 ls -l\r\n\r\nIt basically gave me the positive results and placed them inside the setuidsearch. The executables were placed inside in the ls format. I now had  the list of setuid files the exercise was telling me to look for.\r\n\r\nSetUID ( Set User ID Upon Execution) is pretty self-explanatory. It runs a process with the permissions of the owner of the executable AS ANOTHER USER. This seems a bit confusing, at first, but a perfect example would be the passwd command. The passwd command needs to use protected files that are only accessible to the superusers(root). A setuid passwd command is needed to mediate their access.\r\n\r\nSudo is very similar to passwd. The user accesses files/executable as root user via sudo(with the proper identifications and permissions set, of course.) A setuid is needed to access these files/executable as a user other than root.\r\n\r\nSu is a stronger variation of sudo. Sudo usually requires the user to input their OWN password because sudoers are given certain permissions BY Su. Su is the root user and is given a root shell after the appropriate information is given. Su, however, can be used to login to another user, as well. su <em>password</em> or su <em>login password</em>. These files for verification can only be accessed if there is a setuid setup for su. Without, it can never enter the root user unless it was already root user.\r\n\r\nI chose to stop at three items because it tends to become repetitive. Essentially, setuid allows a user to run a binary as a different level user. There are limitations to the amount of accessibility the user will be granted based on the permissions and they are usually very simple and low end. Ping can be used by a normal user by the more advanced commands such as opening sockets can only be used by root user.</blockquote>','Access Control and Rootly Powers: Exercises','','publish','open','open','','access-control-and-rootly-powers-exercises','','','2013-12-01 22:33:19','2013-12-01 22:33:19','',0,'http://firasimus.com/?p=16',0,'post','',0),(17,1,'2013-12-01 18:52:19','2013-12-01 18:52:19','Use the find command with the -perm option to locate five setuid files on your system. For each file, explain why the setuid mechanism is necessary for the command to function properly.','Access Control and Rootly Powers: Exercises','','inherit','open','open','','16-revision-v1','','','2013-12-01 18:52:19','2013-12-01 18:52:19','',16,'http://firasimus.com/?p=17',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2013-12-01 22:32:37','2013-12-01 22:32:37','<blockquote>Use the find command with the -perm option to locate five setuid fil