ty easy.\r\n\r\nI want all my files to be exactly the same on both domains(firasimus.com AND legacyuo.com). The first issue that came to mind was MySQL - how is the second VPS going to update/read the database of MySQL of the first VPS? Well, making MySQL host remotely to allow Wordpress to access it. Let\'s take a step back and remember something before we begin this.\r\n\r\nWe need to make sure the settings are proper from VPS1 so that VPS2 will work properly, as well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet\'s begin.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn VPS I will access my MySQL.\r\n\r\nmysql -u root -p\r\n\r\nin MySQL you will type( I am going to use my files/names to make it easy)\r\n\r\ngrant all on wordpress.* to \'firaswp\'@\'162.243.67.60\' identified by \'passwordhere\';\r\n\r\nI just granted access to VPS1 FROM VPS1, yes, you need to do that because it will be accessed remotely and not locally in the settings because we will be using universal settings for VPS2 since you are just copying the files to be mounted\r\n\r\nyou then will run\r\n\r\ngrant all on wordpress.* to \'firaswp\'@\'162.243.249.216\' identified by \'passwordhere\';\r\n\r\nI just granted access to the database for user firaswp to the IP of the second VPS. Both IPs now have remote access to the MySQL database. I would then update the wordpress config and point the MySQL hostname to the IP address of the MySQL database host, in this case VPS1 which is essentially 162.243.67.60.\r\n\r\nAgain, remember, VPS1 is the \"local\" MySQL database, but it needs to grant itself access because we are making \"universal\" settings so that the settings can be copied onto numerous VPS\'s as long as their corresponding IP\'s are granted access.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnd that\'s it, simple enough, the MySQL database is being remotely hosted for wordpress to reach.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','MySQL Database Remote Sharing/Hosting','','publish','open','open','','mysql-database-remote-sharinghosting','','','2013-12-16 21:58:39','2013-12-16 21:58:39','',0,'http://firasimus.com/?p=26',0,'post','',0),(27,1,'2013-12-16 21:58:39','2013-12-16 21:58:39','Again, it\'s difficult to remember every little bit of information as you are learning so much and progressing at a decent rate. This is essentially the reason I created this website. I need to be better about actually placing the information via posts much quicker than a couple of days after the completion of a project. Oh well, this helps to refresh/remember all the things I have done, I suppose.\r\n\r\nSo, I\'m planning to host firasimus.com on another domain( the exact site, just another domain). I own legacyuo.com, so I\'ll be using that. The first thing I did was forward my DNS of legacyuo.com to the IP of the second VPS. Pretty easy.\r\n\r\nI want all my files to be exactly the same on both domains(firasimus.com AND legacyuo.com). The first issue that came to mind was MySQL - how is the second VPS going to update/read the database of MySQL of the first VPS? Well, making MySQL host remotely to allow Wordpress to access it. Let\'s take a step back and remember something before we begin this.\r\n\r\nWe need to make sure the settings are proper from VPS1 so that VPS2 will work properly, as well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLet\'s begin.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn VPS I will access my MySQL.\r\n\r\nmysql -u root -p\r\n\r\nin MySQL you will type( I am going to use my files/names to make it easy)\r\n\r\ngrant all on wordpress.* to \'firaswp\'@\'162.243.67.60\' identified by \'passwordhere\';\r\n\r\nI just granted access to VPS1 FROM VPS1, yes, you need to do that because it will be accessed remotely and not locally in the settings because we will be using universal settings for VPS2 since you are just copying the files to be mounted\r\n\r\nyou then will run\r\n\r\ngrant all on wordpress.* to \'firaswp\'@\'162.243.249.216\' identified by \'passwordhere\';\r\n\r\nI just granted access to the database for user firaswp to the IP of the second VPS. Both IPs now have remote access to the MySQL database. I would then update the wordpress config and point the MySQL hostname to the IP address of the MySQL database host, in this case VPS1 which is essentially 162.243.67.60.\r\n\r\nAgain, remember, VPS1 is the \"local\" MySQL database, but it needs to grant itself access because we are making \"universal\" settings so that the settings can be copied onto numerous VPS\'s as long as their corresponding IP\'s are granted access.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAnd that\'s it, simple enough, the MySQL database is being remotely hosted for wordpress to reach.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','MySQL Database Remote Sharing/Hosting','','inherit','open','open','','26-revision-v1','','','2013-12-16 21:58:39','2013-12-16 21:58:39','',26,'http://firasimus.com/?p=27',0,'revision','',0),(28,1,'2013-12-16 23:18:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','The next project I was given was MySQL replication. It\'s essentially used to backup MySQL Databases incase the main MySQL database host crashes for some reason.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nFirst, we need to configure the \"Master\" server. If you have seen my previous posts then you know it\'s going to be VPS1.\n\nnano /etc/my.cnf\n\nAdd these under the [mysqld] section.\n\nlog-bin= firasimus-bin.log\n\nbinlog-do-db=wordpress( thats the database i\'ll be replicating, you can not have this line and it will replicate ALL the databases)\n\nserver-id=1\n\nSave, and exit.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nRestart your MySQL service: service mysqld restart.\n\nLog into your MySQL:\n\nmysql -u root -p\n\nOnce inside the shell type:\n\nGrant Replication slave on *.* to \'slave_user\'@\'162.243.249.216\' identified by \'passwordhere\'\n\nYou can use % to allow from ANY IP, but I wouldn\'t recommend that. You just granted slave replication to the user \'slave_user\' from the IP of 162.243.249.216 ( which will ultimately be one of our slave servers)\n\nFlush privileges;\n\nflush tables with read lock;\n\nshow master status;\n\nRemember this information. You will want the file name which should be firasimus-bin.000 and position #.\n\nYou would then exit mysql and dump the databases.\n\nmysqldump -p --all-databases &gt; mysql.sql\n\nafter it\'s created you need to get this mysql.sql file to VPS2.\n\nscp mysql.sql root@162.243.249.216:/root\n\nyou will be prompted for the password, insert it, and it will copy the dump onto VPS2.\n\nYou will then have to go to VPS2 and forward the settings by using the dump.\n\nOn VPS2:\n\nmysql -p &lt; mysql.sql\n\nLog into mysq','MySQL Replication','','draft','open','open','','','','','2013-12-16 23:18:58','2013-12-16 23:18:58','',0,'http://firasimus.com/?p=28',0,'post','',0);
